@Mugen87 the difference I'm seeing there is the floor color. Background, clear color, and fog were outliers (prior to THREE.ColorManagement) in that they expected user input in the *output* color space (typically sRGB), and did no conversions to/from the working color space.  They should be OK here.

Other material properties were different, expecting input to be in the working color space, Linear-sRGB. This was confusing, as users expect to use the same colors from CSS, HTML, and their color picker, which is what THREE.ColorManagement aims to allow. When we define the ground as...

```js
const ground = new THREE.Mesh(
  new THREE.PlaneGeometry( 2000, 2000 ),
  new THREE.MeshPhongMaterial( { color: 0x999999, depthWrite: false } )
);
```

... a color that was previously interpreted as Linear-sRGB is now interpreted as sRGB, because it is a hexadecimal or CSS-style input, and converted accordingly. The easy fix here would be `ground.material.color.convertLinearToSRGB()`, but we should avoid that fix in examples. It would be confusing, because we're taking a color that was incorrectly converted and bringing it back to Linear, not to sRGB.

Ideally we should just update these colors' hex values, to match their CSS counterparts. But it's also fine with me if we want to just disable `THREE.ColorManagement` on these examples for now, and clean it up in another PR. This will likely affect material colors in any examples that already had `.outputEncoding = sRGBEncoding` enabled.

> **EDIT:** Also — for any examples that still have Linear-sRGB canvas output for legacy reasons, we should wait to update their colors until _both_ sRGB output and ColorManagement are enabled. I would encourage you to keep ColorManagement disabled on examples where `.outputColorSpace = THREE.LinearSRGBColorSpace` for legacy reasons. Either we can clean those up before this PR goes in, or after.

Mainly the problem I'm trying to solve is that users don't know which textures should use which color space (or NoColorSpace). Even if we provided a complete list of recommendations, applying the color spaces correctly to every texture every time is verbose, e.g. in R3F it's something like...

```js
const map = useTexture('path/to/diffuse.png', (texture) => {
  texture.colorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace;
  return texture;
}); 
```

> ...it would be good to know what the expected file format options are for p3 or other wide-gamut color content

I think that's a strength of filename conventions over the original PR here. If the user is authoring wide-gamut content they can simply adjust the map:

```js
THREE.TextureLoader.setColorSpaceRules({
  '_diffuse': THREE.DisplayP3ColorSpace,
  '_emissive': THREE.DisplayP3ColorSpace,
  '_occlusion': THREE.NoColorSpace,
  '_metalness': THREE.NoColorSpace,
  '_roughness': THREE.NoColorSpace,
});
```

I don't necessarily think we should provide any default naming convention – much less one that encompasses wide-gamut color spaces. But I'm looking for methods users can set up once, or copy/paste from an example, rather than thinking about it on every texture load. :/ 

I'm not optimistic about https://github.com/w3c/ColorWeb-CG/issues/112 solving this completely. Even if the feature is added, non-color maps often carry sRGB ICC profiles, and detecting SRGBColorSpace vs. NoColorSpace may remain hard. That may provide enough signal to identify Display P3 images correctly though.

