The original implementation presented in the paper was designed for shaders, some of the assumptions used cannot be easily reproduced or matched in Javascript. As you might've noticed yourself with the problems relating to `NaN` comparisons and `min/max` functions. 

There's also one extra thing to keep in mind, the original implementation was inconsistent when it comes to handling corners, coplanar rays & rays originating from one of the faces. On some instances it treats the bounding box as inclusive, in other cases it doesn't. 

Our current implementation treats all edges/faces inclusively. In order to keep backwards compatibility, it would be preferred to keep it that way.

I've sketched an implementation that tries to accomodate for all of these pre-requisites, and have ran against our current test suite and a few extra edge cases. I haven't, however, ran a more extensive performance test, that would be recommended.

```js
intersectBox( box, target ) {

    const invDist = _vector.set( 1, 1, 1 ).divide( this.direction );

    const t0 = _edge1.copy( box.min ).sub( this.origin ).multiply( invDist );
    t0.set(
        isNaN( t0.x ) ? invDist.x : t0.x,
        isNaN( t0.y ) ? invDist.y : t0.y,
        isNaN( t0.z ) ? invDist.z : t0.z,
    );

    const t1 = _edge2.copy( box.max ).sub( this.origin ).multiply( invDist );
    t1.set(
        isNaN( t1.x ) ? invDist.x : t1.x,
        isNaN( t1.y ) ? invDist.y : t1.y,
        isNaN( t1.z ) ? invDist.z : t1.z,
    );

    const tmin = _vector.copy( t1 ).min( t0 );
    const tmax = t1.max( t0 );

    const pmin = Math.max( tmin.x, Math.max( tmin.y, tmin.z ) );
    const pmax = Math.min( tmax.x, Math.min( tmax.y, tmax.z ) );

    const intersects = pmin <= pmax && ( pmax >= 0 || pmin >= 0 ) && ( isFinite( pmin ) || pmin != pmax );

    if ( ! intersects ) return null;

    return this.at( ( ( pmin * pmax > 0 ) ? pmin : pmax ), target );

}
```

